{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514714"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.13,0.17,0.58,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4876"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93011"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43321"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a two-month history of worsening shortness of breath. He also has a chronic cough, which he attributes to his smoking. He has a medical history of stable angina. He uses sublingual nitroglycerin PRN (approximately twice a month) and takes no other regular medication. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 142/90 mmHg, pulse 86/min and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. He has poor inspiratory effort, and bilateral wheezes can be heard on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESABA: short acting beta agonist, SAMA: short-acting muscarinic antagonist, LABA: long acting beta agonist, LAMA: long acting muscarinic antagonist, ICS: inhaled corticosteroid\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following inhalers would be the most appropriate for his immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Indacaterol (LABA)","Tiotropium (LAMA)","Fluticasone (ICS)","Ipratropium (SAMA)","Eformoterol (LABA)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patients worsening dyspnoea, age and extensive smoking history it is highly likely that he has chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and that this may be his first presentation of COPD to the GP as he is not currently on any inhalers. There is no fever or evidence in the scenario of an infective exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor a first presentation of stable COPD, \u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium bromide\u003C/strong\u003E (SAMA) or a salbutamol inhaler (SABA) are appropriate choices. COPD management should thereafter take a stepwise approach, with the following recommended by guidelines from The Australian Lung Foundation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESABA (e.g salbutamol) OR SAMA (e.g ipratropium) to use as needed (PRN)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdd\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003ELABA OR LAMA (e.g eformoterol + tiotropium)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsider need to add a combination LABA/LAMA inhaler depending on symptom control\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdd\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003EICS (e.g fluticasone) on top of LABA/LAMA combination (e.g. triple therapy)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore the other options including \u003Cstrong\u003Eindacaterol \u003C/strong\u003E(LABA), \u003Cstrong\u003Etiotropium \u003C/strong\u003E(LAMA), \u003Cstrong\u003Eeformoterol \u003C/strong\u003E(LABA), \u003Cstrong\u003Efluticasone \u003C/strong\u003E(ICS) are incorrect as they are second/third line medications, not first line for COPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is vital to remember that non-pharmacological management must always come first including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEncouraging smoking cessation or at least reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary rehabilitation and regular exercise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVaccination (influenza yearly and pneumococcal vaccine)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is also worth being familiar with common inhaler brand and pharmacological names e.g Ventolin = salbutamol, Atrovent= ipratropium. The list of inhalers available in Australia can be found in the references.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first step in the pharmacological management of COPD is a SABA (e.g salbutamol) OR SAMA (e.g ipratropium) inhaler - which are used as needed","Non pharmacological management of COPD include smoking cessation, pulmonary rehabilitation and vaccination."],"references":["Almadhoun K, Sharma S. Bronchodilators. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Nov 14. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519028/","COPD-X Plan. In: Lung Foundation Australia. 2022. Available at: https://copdx.org.au/copd-x-plan/","Stepwise management of stable COPD. In: Lung Foundation Australia. Available at: https://lungfoundation.com.au/resources/stepwise-management-of-stable-copd/","COPD Inhaler Chart. In: Lung Foundation Australia. 2024. Available at: https://lungfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/COPD-Inhaler-Poster-A3_JUNE2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93011"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-04T10:38:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-04T10:38:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4876"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"